  "text": "The Kubernetes scheduler plugin framework is a comprehensive system that allows extensibility of the scheduler through plugins. Here are the key components:\n\n**1. Framework Interface Definitions (pkg/scheduler/framework/interface.go):**\nThis file defines all plugin interfaces that follow a parent Plugin interface. The main plugin interfaces are:\n- PreEnqueuePlugin: Called before pods are added to the active queue\n- QueueSortPlugin: Sorts pods in the scheduling queue (only one enabled at a time)\n- EnqueueExtensions: Optional interface for efficient pod movement in scheduling queues\n- PreFilterPlugin: Called at the beginning of a scheduling cycle; can return PreFilterResult to influence which nodes to evaluate\n- FilterPlugin: Filters out hosts that cannot run a pod (formerly called 'predicates')\n- PostFilterPlugin: Called after a pod cannot be scheduled; used for preemption logic\n- PreScorePlugin: Informational extension point after filtering; plugins can update internal state\n- ScorePlugin: Ranks nodes that passed the filtering phase; must implement Score() and optionally ScoreExtensions() with NormalizeScore()\n- ReservePlugin: Updates plugin state when scheduler cache is updated; has Reserve() and Unreserve() methods\n- PreBindPlugin: Called before a pod is bound to a node\n- BindPlugin: Binds a pod to a node (at most one BindPlugin handles the binding)\n- PostBindPlugin: Called after a pod is successfully bound; used for cleanup\n- PermitPlugin: Called before binding; can prevent or delay pod binding\n\nAll plugins implement the Plugin interface which requires a Name() method. The Framework interface is the main contract that aggregates all plugin-related functionality.\n\n**2. ScheduleOne Orchestration (pkg/scheduler/schedule_one.go):**\nThe ScheduleOne() function (line 65) is the main entry point that orchestrates the scheduling workflow for a single pod. It:\n- Gets the next pod from the scheduling queue via NextPod()\n- Retrieves the appropriate framework for the pod\n- Creates a fresh CycleState for the scheduling cycle\n- Calls schedulingCycle() which invokes the scheduling plugins in sequence\n- On success, asynchronously calls bindingCycle() to bind the pod\n\n**3. Top-Level Scheduler Struct (pkg/scheduler/scheduler.go):**\nThe Scheduler struct (line 66) is the main component that watches for new unscheduled pods and attempts to find suitable nodes. The Run() method (line 464) starts the scheduler in a goroutine, initializing the scheduling queue and the scheduleOne loop.\n\n**4. FrameworkImpl Runtime (pkg/scheduler/framework/runtime/framework.go):**\nThe frameworkImpl struct (line 52) is responsible for initializing and running scheduler plugins. Key methods include:\n- RunPreFilterPlugins() (line 697): Runs PreFilter plugins; returns PreFilterResult and status\n- RunFilterPlugins() (line 872): Runs Filter plugins; returns status for each node\n- RunPostFilterPlugins() (line 919): Runs PostFilter plugins for preemption\n- RunPreScorePlugins() (line 1075): Runs PreScore plugins\n- RunScorePlugins() (line 1112): Runs Score plugins in parallel and handles score normalization\nThe frameworkImpl maintains lists of all configured plugins for each extension point and orchestrates their execution with proper error handling and metrics recording.\n\n**5. Plugin Registry (pkg/scheduler/framework/runtime/registry.go and pkg/scheduler/framework/plugins/registry.go):**\nThe Registry type (line 71 in registry.go) is a map[string]PluginFactory that holds all available plugins. The NewInTreeRegistry() function (pkg/scheduler/framework/plugins/registry.go, line 47) builds the registry with all in-tree plugins including:\n- DynamicResources, ImageLocality, TaintToleration, NodeName, NodePorts\n- NodeAffinity, PodTopologySpread, NodeUnschedulable, NodeResources\n- VolumeBinding, VolumeRestrictions, VolumeZone, NodeVolumeLimits\n- InterPodAffinity, QueueSort, DefaultBinder, DefaultPreemption, SchedulingGates\n\nThe Registry supports Register(), Unregister(), and Merge() operations. Out-of-tree plugins can be registered via the WithFrameworkOutOfTreeRegistry option when building the scheduler.\n\nThe complete scheduling pipeline flows: Scheduler.Run() → ScheduleOne() → schedulingCycle() → RunPreFilterPlugins() → RunFilterPlugins() → RunScorePlugins() → bindingCycle() with various other plugins invoked at appropriate extension points throughout the cycle."
